      },
      "date": "2021-10-22 15:48:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review\n\nWait I thought their was a bool state that matters for this. Amir?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "04f9fb1b3cceb1f2feaf01ba5dbf84d99841d269",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-25 16:50:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPing for review",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7405959aab14f6745ffdd0cc7123bcaf3e68f708",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 824,
        "name": "Serguei Smirnov",
        "email": "ssmirnov@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ssmirnov"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-25 19:46:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIn kiblnd_net_init_pools lnd_map_on_demand is used to determine whether to use FMR/FastReg or use global MR. If negotiation failed with IBLND_REJECT_RDMA_FRAGS, it can be because the number of fragments didn't match and FMR/FastReg is disabled. Why not notify that map_on_demand should be enabled in this case if it is disabled?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7aee2db7a978b132e27a921756d211bcbeff138e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-25 20:43:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThat's a fair point, but we can't actually detect that situation can we? It _may_ be the case that we need to enable map_on_demand, or it may be the case that we can already negotiate max frags.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "119ce69d27226f5168df09b27eab7de5c0507edc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-25 20:44:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "bfca52356b726ef955dab4fa0440a15c534a436e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 824,
        "name": "Serguei Smirnov",
        "email": "ssmirnov@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ssmirnov"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-25 20:52:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> (1 comment)\n\nThe case I was talking about is \"(reqmsg->ibm_u.connparams.ibcp_max_frags < IBLND_MAX_RDMA_FRAGS && net->ibn_fmr_ps == NULL)\". \nnet->ibn_fmr_ps == NULL is the result of map_on_demand being disabled. So yes, I think it would make sense to mention it when giving the reason for the negotiation failure.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9a41efd343433d77ab361fae0b7c1a9b43f5f42d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-25 20:56:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> > (1 comment)\n > \n > The case I was talking about is \"(reqmsg->ibm_u.connparams.ibcp_max_frags\n > < IBLND_MAX_RDMA_FRAGS && net->ibn_fmr_ps == NULL)\".\n > net->ibn_fmr_ps == NULL is the result of map_on_demand being\n > disabled. So yes, I think it would make sense to mention it when\n > giving the reason for the negotiation failure.\n\nRight, but that's on the passive connection side. AFAICT, we cannot detect this situation on the active side (which is what this mod touches).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0de60760d264e7d2770fc9378f5cf76f8382f383",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 824,
        "name": "Serguei Smirnov",
        "email": "ssmirnov@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "ssmirnov"
      },
      "date": "2021-10-26 22:25:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n> > > (1 comment)\n > >\n > > The case I was talking about is \"(reqmsg->ibm_u.connparams.ibcp_max_frags\n > > < IBLND_MAX_RDMA_FRAGS && net->ibn_fmr_ps == NULL)\".\n > > net->ibn_fmr_ps == NULL is the result of map_on_demand being\n > > disabled. So yes, I think it would make sense to mention it when\n > > giving the reason for the negotiation failure.\n > \n > Right, but that's on the passive connection side. AFAICT, we cannot\n > detect this situation on the active side (which is what this mod\n > touches).\n\nI think I see what you mean. Indeed it looks like all we can report here is just that max frags didn't match.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "71e185b7e7613e05200240bfb730cff640dc61c3",
